'''CPU shielding''' is a practice where on a multiprocessor system or on a CPU with multiple cores, [[Real-time computing|real-time]] tasks can run on one CPU or core while non-real-time tasks run on another.

The [[operating system]] must be able to set a [[CPU affinity]] for both [[Process (computing)|processes]] and [[interrupt]]s.

== Kernel space ==
In [[Linux]] in order to shield [[Central processing unit|CPU]]s from individual interrupts being serviced on them you have to make sure that the following [[Linux kernel|kernel]] configuration parameter is set:
* CONFIG_IRQBALANCE

