{{Infobox company |name = Multibeam Corporation |foundation = {{start date and age|2010}} |location = [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]], [[California]] |key_people = [[David Lam (tech entrepreneur)|David K. Lam]] <small>([[Chairman]])</small> |products = [[Electron-beam lithography|E-beam lithography]] systems for the [[semiconductor]] industry |industry = [[Semiconductor industry]] |homepage = http://www.multibeamcorp.com }}
'''Multibeam''' is an American corporation that engages in the design of [[semiconductor]] processing equipment used in the [[Semiconductor device fabrication|fabrication of integrated circuits]]. Based in [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]], in the [[Silicon Valley]], Multibeam is led by [[David Lam (tech entrepreneur)|Dr. David K. Lam]], the founder and first CEO of [[Lam Research]].
==Technology== Multibeam developed miniature, all-electrostatic columns for [[Electron-beam lithography|e-beam lithography]]. Arrays of e-beam columns operate simultaneously and in parallel to increase [[Wafer (electronics)|wafer]] processing speed. With 36 patents filed,<ref name=SST>{{cite web|title=Multibeam Patents Direct Deposition & Direct Etch|url=http://semimd.com/blog/2016/11/14/multibeam-patents-direct-deposition-direct-etch/|publisher=Solid State Technology|date=November 14, 2016}}</ref> Multibeam develops multicolumn e-beam systems and platforms for four major applications: Complementary E-Beam Lithography (CEBL), Direct Electron Writing (DEW), Direct Deposition/Etch (DDE), and E-Beam Inspection (EBI)<ref name=SST/>
==Applications==
* Direct Electron Writing (DEW) embeds security information in each IC including [[Serial code|chip ID]], [[IP address|IP]] or [[MAC address|MAC]] address, and chip-specific information such as [[Key (cryptography)|keys]] used in [[Public-key cryptography|encryption]]. Chip ID is used for supply chain traceability and to detect counterfeits. Hardware-embedded encryption keys are used to authenticate software. Chip-specific information written into DEW-bit registers is non-volatile.<ref>{{cite web|title=Securing Chips During Manufacturing|url=http://semiengineering.com/securing-chips-during-manufacturing/|publisher=Semiconductor Engineering|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tech Talk|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALCEMN5iFmM|publisher=eBeam Initiative|date=October 2016}}</ref> * Complementary Electron Beam Lithography (CEBL) works with [[Photolithography|optical lithography]] to pattern cuts (of lines in "lines-and-cuts" layout)<ref>{{cite web|title=1D design style implications for mask making and CEBL|url=http://proceedings.spiedigitallibrary.org/proceeding.aspx?articleid=1736344|publisher=SPIE|date=September 9, 2013}}</ref> and holes (i.e., [[Ohmic contact|contacts]] and [[Via (electronics)|vias]]) with no masks.<ref>{{cite web|title=From the White Board|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2ZCF-o7DXlU|publisher=eBeam Initiative|date=June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Multiple columns for high-throughput complementary e-beam lithography (CEBL)|url=https://spie.org/Publications/Proceedings/Paper/10.1117/12.916118|publisher=SPIE|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=E-beam to complement optical lithography for 1D layouts|url=https://spie.org/Publications/Proceedings/Paper/10.1117/12.879479|publisher=SPIE|date=April 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=E-beam direct write (EBDW) as complementary lithography|url=https://spie.org/Publications/Proceedings/Paper/10.1117/12.868485|publisher=SPIE|date=September 29, 2010}}</ref> * Direct Deposition/Etch (DDE) can be used in [[Semiconductor device fabrication|chip fabrication]] or wafer defect repair. Precursors or reactants are introduced through gas injectors. Activation electrons are directed in accordance with the design [[Integrated circuit layout|layout]] database to [[Electron beam-induced deposition|deposit]] or [[Reactive-ion etching|remove]] material at precise locations on the substrate.<ref name=SST/><ref>{{cite web|title=Precision deposition using miniature-column charged particle beam arrays |url=https://www.google.com/patents/US9453281|date=September 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Precision substrate material removal using miniature-column charged particle beam arrays |url=https://www.google.com/patents/US9466464|date=October 11, 2016}}</ref> * Multi-column Electron Beam Inspection (EBI) for wafer defect detection and [[metrology]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Charged particle beam substrate inspection using both vector and raster scanning|url=https://www.google.com/patents/US9466463|date=October 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Matched multiple charged particle beam systems for lithographic patterning, inspection, and accelerated yield ramp|url=https://www.google.com/patents/US8999627|date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Multiple column high-throughput e-beam inspection (EBI)|url=https://spie.org/Publications/Proceedings/Paper/10.1117/12.927032|publisher=SPIE|date=April 5, 2012}}</ref>
